		<description><![CDATA[<p>A writer and cultural anthropologist, Bateson is a visiting scholar at Boston College’s Center on Aging and Work. She was born in New York City in 1939 and lived there until 1956 when she traveled to Israel, leaning Hebrew and completing the Israeli matriculation exams. After she returned to the United States, she attended Radcliffe</p><p>The post <a href="http://www.macmillanspeakers.com/marycatherinebateson">Professor Emerita, Cultural Anthropologist</a> appeared first on <a href="http://www.macmillanspeakers.com">Macmillan Speakers Bureau</a>.</p>]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>A writer and cultural anthropologist, Bateson is a visiting scholar at Boston College’s Center on Aging and Work. She was born in New York City in 1939 and lived there until 1956 when she traveled to Israel, leaning Hebrew and completing the Israeli matriculation exams. After she returned to the United States, she attended Radcliffe College and then when to graduate school at Harvard University, where she studied Arabic linguistics and Islamic history.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Her first teaching job was at Harvard, followed by two years in the Philippines and later in Iran. Bateson was Dean of the Faculty at Amherst College from 1980 to 1983, and from 1987 to 2002, she was the Claren J. Robinson Professor in Anthropology and English at George Mason University and became Professor <i>Emerita</i> in 2002. After that, she spent three years as Visiting Professor at the Harvard Graduate School of Education and also taught at Northeastern University and Spelman College.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>While her original research interest was in the Middle East, she has more recently been interested in how women and men work out distinctive ways of adapting to culture change, learning from those around them, and improvising new ways of being. This has led her to work with life histories and other types of first person narratives. Bateson was also president of the Institute for Intercultural Studies in New York City from 1979 to 2009. She has written and co-authored numerous books and articles as well as lectured across the country and around the world to professional and popular audiences.</p>
<p>The post <a href="http://www.macmillanspeakers.com/marycatherinebateson">Professor Emerita, Cultural Anthropologist</a> appeared first on <a href="http://www.macmillanspeakers.com">Macmillan Speakers Bureau</a>.</p>]]></content:encoded>
